  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "oOS4+sd1Xuj2YesMWJ3LZ3kxIEA=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nThe throughput ceiling on a single feed is **network propagation of the SOC through the responsible neighborhood**, not the bandwidth between the client and its Bee node.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Bee processes feed writes sequentially per topic because SOC index is monotonic\n- A newly-written SOC at index N must be stored by the responsible neighborhood before a reader at any other node will see it \u2014 and therefore before index N+1's causal \"based on\" is reliable\n- The adapter's 3-second debounce already batches rapid edits into single writes, so per-topic write rate is typically well below the propagation limit\n- The throttled flush (max 5 concurrent writes) prevents overloading the node across topics\n- Quoted key insight from source: *\"the bottleneck is not upload speed but feed propagation time (SOC must be stored by the neighborhood before the next write is visible).\"*\n\n## Why it matters\n\nTuning the debounce window smaller than propagation time buys nothing \u2014 you just queue writes behind each other. It reframes performance work: invest in propagation-side strategies (mutable stamps, GSOC notifications, advance retrieve requests) rather than client upload parallelism for single-feed scenarios.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
